cs.DS, cs.CE, cs.DM, cs.LG, cs.IT

Reasoning: 
- cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) is the most likely category as the paper proposes a new algorithm based on the suffix tree of a string and a small data structure built on the Burrows-Wheeler transform to efficiently detect unusual words in a text. 
- cs.CE (Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science) is also likely as the paper mentions the scalability of the algorithm to genomes or metagenomes, which are common in computational biology and bioinformatics. 
- cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) is another possible category as the paper deals with the problem of detecting unusual words in a text, which can be seen as a problem in combinatorics and discrete mathematics. 
- cs.LG (Machine Learning) is a possible category as the paper mentions the scoring of candidate under-represented strings, which can be seen as a classification problem. 
- cs.IT (Information Theory) is another possible category as the paper deals with the problem of detecting strings that occur more or less frequently than expected according to an IID or a Markov model, which can be seen as a problem in information theory.
